The 7ft 3in long figure, which has become a well-known fixture of the Moore Sculpture Gallery extension, will be cleaned and renovated when the exhibition ends in September before being returned.

The artist - who was the son of a coal miner - was best known for his semi-abstract monumental bronze sculptures which are now located in public spaces in cities around the world.

His forms are usually abstractions of the human figure, typically depicting mother-and-child or reclining figures. Moore's works are usually suggestive of the female body, apart from a phase in the 1950s when he sculpted family groups.

His forms are generally pierced or contain hollow spaces. Many interpreters liken the undulating form of his reclining figures to the landscape and hills of his birthplace in Yorkshire.

